Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". dia do prep, poss (Hand10) 2.1 MS9.7r.4 et  reliqua  ag iarraidh righe dia

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.

iarraidh iarraid vnoun (Hand10) 2.1 MS9.7r.4 {sr[u]  mac }eassru  et  reliqua  ag iarraidh righe dia 

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.

ag oc prep (Hand10) 2.1 MS9.7r.4 .i. {sr[u]  mac }eassru  et  reliqua  ag iarraidh righe dia 

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.

righe ríge noun (Hand10) 2.1 MS9.7r.4 eassru  et  reliqua  ag iarraidh righe dia 

Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.
